{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11770"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11770"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.58,0.18,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4383"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93629"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"435"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40273"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of gradual loss of vision in her right eye. She has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. Her medications include amlodipine and rosuvastatin. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her visual acuity is 6/48 in the right eye and 6/9 in the left eye. Intraocular pressures are 18 mmHg in both eyes. There is no relative afferent pupillary defect. Fundoscopy is performed (Image). OCT of the macula in the right eye shows intraretinal fluid accumulation\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral steroids","Intravitreal anti-VEGF injection","Laser photocoagulation","Ocular massage","Anticoagulation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus photograph shows tortuous and dilated retinal veins in all four quadrants of the retina with areas of retinal haemorrhage. These findings are consistent with central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO), when there is a thrombus in the central retinal vein as it passes through the lamina cribrosa. There may also be cotton wool spots and a positive closing pressure sign. It is associated with cardiovacscular risk factors such as hyperlipidaemia and hypertension as in this case, as well as diabetes, smoking, myeloproliferative disease and the oral contraceptive pill. As such, management also involves optimising these cardiovascular risk factors. Patients must be aware of the complications of neovascular glaucoma, vitreous haemorrhage, and tractional retinal detachment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravitreal anti-VEGF injection\u003C/strong\u003E. Anti-VEGF therapy, such as bevacizumab, ranibizumab, or aflibercept, is the first-line treatment for macular oedema secondary to CRVO. These agents reduce vascular permeability and inhibit neovascularisation, thereby improving visual acuity and reducing macular oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral steroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically used as first-line treatment for CRVO. While intravitreal steroid injections may be considered in some cases, they are generally reserved for patients who do not respond to or cannot tolerate anti-VEGF therapy due to the risk of increased intraocular pressure and cataract formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary treatment for macular oedema in CRVO. It may be used in cases of neovascularisation, particularly for peripheral retinal ischaemia, but it is not the first-line treatment for the macular oedema that typically causes vision loss in CRVO. This patient will need to be observed for signs of neovascularization in which then laser treatment is indicated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOcular massage\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate treatment for CRVO. This technique is sometimes used in cases of central retinal artery occlusion to attempt to dislodge an embolus, but it has no role in the management of CRVO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for the treatment of CRVO. While CRVO is a thrombotic event, studies have not shown a clear benefit of anticoagulation in its management. The focus of treatment is on managing macular oedema and preventing complications rather than addressing the initial thrombotic event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central retinal vein occlusion shows evidence of tortuous, dilated veins with areas of retinal haemorrhage.","Intravitreal anti-VEGF therapy is the first-line treatment for macular oedema secondary to central retinal vein occlusion."],"references":["Bowling, B. Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). 2015. W B Saunders","Sivaprasad S, Amoaku WM, Hykin P, RVO Guideline Group. The Royal College of Opthalmologists Guidelines on retinal vein occlusions: executive summary. Eye. 2015:20 (1633-1638). Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/eye2015164"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93629"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11770"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15515"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15515"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a153c8f8-6cb2-4c5a-8b55-cdf987e232b0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a153c8f8-6cb2-4c5a-8b55-cdf987e232b0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":567,"height":433}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93629"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-16T13:19:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T07:37:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4383"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/73"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Post-graduate","synonyms":null,"description":"Not sui